  questions:[
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'JavaScript',title:'Q1 — var, let, and const',prompt:'Explain the difference between var, let, and const.',answer:'var is function-scoped, hoisted with a default value of undefined, and can be redeclared and reassigned. let and const are block-scoped and hoisted into a "temporal dead zone" — they exist but throw a ReferenceError if accessed before their declaration line runs. let can be reassigned but not redeclared in the same scope; const cannot be reassigned, though an object or array it points to can still have its contents mutated.',expected:['Scope','Hoisting','Reassignment','Redeclaration','Temporal Dead Zone'],followup:'When should we use const?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'React',title:'Q2 — React Component Lifecycle',prompt:'Explain the React Component Lifecycle.',answer:'Class components go through Mounting (constructor → render → componentDidMount), Updating (render → componentDidUpdate on a prop/state change), and Unmounting (componentWillUnmount). Function components use useEffect() instead: no dependency array runs the effect after every render, an empty array [] runs it once on mount, and a returned cleanup function runs before unmount or before the effect re-runs. In development-only Strict Mode, React intentionally mounts, unmounts, and remounts once to surface effects that don\'t clean up properly — that\'s why useEffect can appear to fire twice.',expected:['Mounting','Updating','Unmounting','useEffect()','Cleanup Function'],followup:'Why does useEffect run twice in React Strict Mode?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'REST APIs',title:'Q3 — JWT Authentication',prompt:'What is JWT Authentication?',answer:'A JWT has three base64-encoded, dot-separated parts: a Header (algorithm/type), a Payload (claims like user id, role, expiry), and a Signature, created by hashing the header and payload with a secret key so the server can detect tampering. On login the server issues the token; the client sends it on each request (typically an Authorization: Bearer header); the server verifies the signature and expiry before trusting the payload. For storage: httpOnly cookies resist XSS better than localStorage on the web; React Native has no cookie jar, so apps typically use secure storage like the device keychain via a library, not plain AsyncStorage for anything sensitive.',expected:['Header','Payload','Signature','Login Flow','Token Validation'],followup:'Where should JWT be stored? Cookie? Local Storage? AsyncStorage? Why?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'REST APIs',title:'Q4 — REST API Fundamentals',prompt:'Explain REST API.',answer:'REST APIs use HTTP methods to represent operations on resources: GET reads, POST creates, PUT replaces a full resource, PATCH updates part of a resource, and DELETE removes it. Status codes communicate the outcome — 2xx success, 4xx client error (400 bad request, 401 unauthorized, 404 not found), 5xx server error. PUT is idempotent and expects the entire resource in the request body; PATCH sends only the fields that actually changed.',expected:['GET','POST','PUT','PATCH','DELETE','Status Codes'],followup:'Difference between PUT and PATCH.'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'MongoDB',title:'Q5 — MongoDB Aggregation',prompt:'Suppose you have a Users collection and an Orders collection. How will you fetch: User Name, Total Orders, Total Amount?',answer:'Use an aggregation pipeline: $lookup joins Orders to Users on a shared field like userId, $group sums the order amounts and counts orders per user, and $project shapes the final output to just the fields you want (name, totalOrders, totalAmount). This does the join and aggregation inside the database in one round trip, instead of pulling everything into the app and calculating there.',expected:['Aggregation','$lookup','Pipeline'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Node.js',title:'Q6 — Node.js Event Loop',prompt:'Explain the Event Loop.',answer:'Node runs JavaScript on a single thread. Synchronous code executes on the call stack; I/O callbacks and timers (setTimeout) go into the event queue (macrotasks); promise callbacks (.then, async/await continuations) go into the microtask queue. The microtask queue is fully drained before the event loop moves to the next macrotask — which is why a resolved promise\'s .then() runs before a setTimeout(fn, 0) callback, even though both were scheduled at the same time.',expected:['Call Stack','Event Queue','Microtask Queue','Promises','setTimeout'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Node.js',title:'Q7 — Project Verification: AI Interview Platform',prompt:'You mentioned the AI Interview Platform. Explain the Architecture, Frontend, Backend, Gemini Integration, Database, Authentication, Deployment.',answer:'There\'s no single correct answer — this is about verifying the candidate actually built it. Listen for a clear, confident walk-through of their own architecture (React/React Native frontend talking to a Node/Express backend, MongoDB for storage, JWT for auth) and a specific explanation of how the Gemini API is called and where. A strong follow-up answer on latency mentions caching repeated prompts, streaming partial responses back to the user, and setting a timeout with a graceful fallback message rather than leaving the UI hanging.',expected:['Architecture','Frontend','Backend','Gemini Integration','Database','Authentication','Deployment'],followup:'If the Gemini API becomes slow, how will you optimize it?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Coding',title:'Q8 — Coding: findDuplicate',prompt:'Write a function findDuplicate([1,2,3,4,5,2,4])\nExpected output: [2,4]',code:'function findDuplicate(arr){\n  const seen = new Set(), dupes = new Set();\n  for (const n of arr){\n    if (seen.has(n)) dupes.add(n);\n    seen.add(n);\n  }\n  return [...dupes];\n}\n// findDuplicate([1,2,3,4,5,2,4]) → [2,4]',answer:'Track values already seen in a Set; if a value shows up again, add it to a second "duplicates" Set (which naturally avoids adding the same duplicate twice). This runs in O(n) time with O(n) extra space — much better than a nested-loop O(n²) approach.',expected:['Logic','Time Complexity','Code Quality','Edge Cases'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Coding',title:'Q9 — Coding: Reverse Every Word',prompt:'Input: "Hello World From OTT"\nOutput: "olleH dlroW morF TTO"',code:'"Hello World From OTT"\n  .split(\' \')\n  .map(w => w.split(\'\').reverse().join(\'\'))\n  .join(\' \');\n// → "olleH dlroW morF TTO"',answer:'Split the sentence into words, reverse the characters of each word individually, then rejoin the reversed words with spaces — note the word order stays the same, only the letters inside each word flip.',expected:['String Manipulation','Loops','JavaScript Methods'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'React',title:'Q10 — OTT App: 200 Movies on Home Screen',prompt:'Netflix Home Screen contains 200 movies. How will you optimize loading?',answer:'Don\'t render or fetch all 200 at once. Paginate the API and lazy-load additional rows as the user scrolls, use FlatList (React Native) or a virtualization library (React) so only visible cards are actually mounted in the DOM, cache poster images so they aren\'t re-downloaded, and show skeleton placeholders while data loads so the screen doesn\'t feel frozen.',expected:['Pagination','Lazy Loading','FlatList','Image Caching','Virtualization','API Pagination','Skeleton Loader'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Scenario',cat:'Scenario Handling',title:'Scenario 1 — Production Login Failure',prompt:'Users are unable to log in. How will you debug?',answer:'Work backward from the user: check the browser Network tab for the actual HTTP status code returned by the login request, check backend/server logs for exceptions around that time, verify the JWT is being generated and signed correctly, and confirm the database connection and user lookup are working. The specific status code (401 vs 500 vs a network failure/timeout) usually narrows the cause immediately.',expected:['Backend Logs','Network Tab','JWT','Database','API','Status Code','Server Logs'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Scenario',cat:'Scenario Handling',title:'Scenario 2 — App Slows After 30 Minutes',prompt:'Users say the app becomes slow after 30 minutes. How will you investigate?',answer:'This pattern usually points to a memory leak: event listeners or intervals not being cleaned up, a useEffect missing its cleanup function, state that keeps growing (e.g. appending to an array on every poll instead of replacing it), or images/data accumulating in memory over time. Use the browser\'s Performance/Memory profiler to take heap snapshots a few minutes apart and see exactly what\'s growing.',expected:['Memory Leak','Infinite Rendering','Large State','Images','Profiler','Performance Monitor'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Logic',cat:'Logic Building',title:'Logical Reasoning — 8 Balls, 2 Weighings',prompt:'You have 8 balls. One ball is heavier. Find it in only 2 weighings.',answer:'Split into groups of 3, 3, and 2. Weigh 3 vs 3. If they balance, the heavy ball is one of the remaining 2 — weigh those two against each other to find it. If they don\'t balance, take the heavier group of 3, weigh 1 of them against another (setting the third aside) — if those two balance, the one set aside is the heavy ball; otherwise, whichever pan is heavier holds the answer.',expected:['Problem Solving','Approach','Logic'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Communication',cat:'Communication',title:'Communication — Pitch to Non-Technical HR',prompt:'Explain your AI Interview Platform to a non-technical HR within 2 minutes.',answer:'There\'s no fixed script here — score on delivery. A strong answer describes the product in outcome terms ("it helps job seekers practice interviews and get instant feedback on their answers") rather than jargon like "Gemini API integration" or "JWT auth," stays under two minutes, and sounds confident rather than memorized.',expected:['Confidence','Communication','Structure','Simple Language'],followup:null},
