    {sec:'Technical',cat:'.NET Core',title:'Q1 — Dependency Injection',prompt:'Explain Dependency Injection in .NET Core.',answer:'ASP.NET Core has a built-in IoC container. Instead of a class creating its own dependencies (tight coupling), it declares what it needs via its constructor and the container injects the right implementation — this makes classes far easier to unit test (you inject mocks) and lets you swap implementations without touching the consuming class. AddSingleton() creates one instance for the entire app lifetime, AddScoped() creates one instance per HTTP request, and AddTransient() creates a brand new instance every time it\'s requested. Getting lifetimes wrong — like injecting a scoped DbContext into a singleton service — causes subtle bugs and memory issues.',expected:['Why DI is used','IOC Container','Constructor Injection','Loose Coupling','Testability'],followup:'Difference between AddSingleton(), AddScoped(), and AddTransient().'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Hangfire',title:'Q2 — Hangfire Internals',prompt:'Your resume mentions Hangfire. Explain how Hangfire works internally.',answer:'Hangfire runs background jobs outside the normal request/response cycle. It persists job data (arguments, state, retry count) to a storage backend like SQL Server or Redis so jobs survive an app restart, and it retries failed jobs automatically with backoff. A scheduler thread pulls jobs off a queue and executes them, and the Hangfire Dashboard gives you a UI to see scheduled, running, succeeded, and failed jobs. Versus a Windows Service, Hangfire needs no separate deployment, comes with the dashboard and persistence/retry logic for free, and is much less code to maintain.',expected:['Background Jobs','Persistent Storage','Retry Mechanism','Job Scheduler','Dashboard','Queue'],followup:'Why use Hangfire instead of Windows Service?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Entity Framework',title:'Q3 — EF Tracking vs No Tracking',prompt:'Explain Entity Framework Tracking vs No Tracking.',answer:'By default, EF Core\'s Change Tracker watches every entity you query so it can detect changes and generate the right UPDATE statements on SaveChanges(). For read-only queries — like a GET endpoint that just returns data — that tracking overhead is wasted; .AsNoTracking() skips it, which is faster and uses less memory. Tracking should stay on any time you intend to modify and save the entity afterward.',expected:['Change Tracker','AsNoTracking()','Performance','Read-only APIs'],followup:'When should Tracking NOT be used?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'SQL Server',title:'Q4 — SQL Performance at Scale',prompt:'Employee table has 20 million records. Search API takes 8 seconds. How will you optimize it?',answer:'Start with the execution plan to check whether the query is doing a full table scan. Add an index on the columns used in WHERE/JOIN/ORDER BY, avoid SELECT * (fetch only needed columns), paginate results instead of returning everything, and consider a stored procedure for complex multi-step logic to cut down round trips. A clustered index physically orders the table\'s data (only one allowed per table, great for primary keys and range queries); a non-clustered index is a separate lookup structure (many allowed per table), good for columns that are filtered on often but aren\'t the primary key.',expected:['Indexes','Execution Plan','Pagination','Stored Procedure','Avoid SELECT *','Query Optimization'],followup:'Clustered vs Non-Clustered Index?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'C#',title:'Q5 — JWT Login Flow',prompt:'Explain complete JWT Login Flow.',answer:'On login, the server verifies the password (hashed comparison, never plaintext), generates a short-lived JWT access token containing claims like user id and role, signed with a server secret, and issues a longer-lived refresh token stored securely. Middleware validates the JWT\'s signature and expiry on every subsequent request and populates the request\'s user identity/claims from it. When the access token expires, the client calls a refresh endpoint with the refresh token to get a new access token without forcing the user to log in again.',expected:['Login','Verify Password','Generate JWT','Refresh Token','Authorization','Middleware'],followup:'Where should Refresh Token be stored?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'.NET Core',title:'Q6 — Azure Deployment Debugging',prompt:'Your API works locally but fails after deployment. How will you debug?',answer:'Check Azure Monitor / Application Insights logs first for the actual exception — that names the real failure instead of guessing. The most common causes are connection strings or environment variables not matching between local appsettings.json and Azure App Settings, missing IIS/Azure permissions, or a different .NET runtime version deployed than what was tested locally.',expected:['Logs','App Settings','Connection String','Environment Variables','Azure Monitor','IIS Logs'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'API Design',title:'Q7 — Project Verification: LawRep',prompt:'You mentioned developing backend services. Explain Architecture, Database Design, APIs, Authentication, Deployment, Biggest Challenge.',answer:'No fixed answer — this checks whether the candidate genuinely built what\'s on their resume. Listen for specific, confident detail (actual table names, actual API routes, a real challenge with a real resolution) rather than generic textbook description. Vague or contradictory answers about their own project is the clearest red flag in the whole interview.',expected:['Architecture','Database Design','APIs','Authentication','Deployment','Biggest Challenge'],followup:null,redflag:'If candidate cannot explain own project, reduce score.'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'API Design',title:'Q8 — Coding: GET /employees',prompt:'Write an API GET /employees with Pagination, Sorting, Search.',code:'GET /employees?page=1&pageSize=20&sortBy=name&search=john',answer:'A clean implementation separates concerns: the Controller receives the request and query params (page, pageSize, sortBy, search), a Service applies business logic, and a Repository builds the EF Core query using .Where() for search, .OrderBy() for sorting, and .Skip()/.Take() for pagination — then results are mapped to a DTO before returning. Never expose your EF entities directly in the API response.',expected:['Controller','Service','Repository','DTO','LINQ'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'C#',title:'Q9 — Coding: LINQ Even Numbers',prompt:'Given List<int> {1,2,3,4,5,6}, return only even numbers using LINQ.',code:'var evens = nums.Where(n => n % 2 == 0).ToList();\n// → {2, 4, 6}',answer:'.Where() filters a sequence down to elements matching a condition. Select() projects/transforms each element into something else (e.g. mapping entities to DTOs). Any() returns a bool for whether at least one element matches a condition. First() returns the first matching element and throws if none exist — FirstOrDefault() is the null-safe version.',expected:['Code Quality','LINQ Knowledge'],followup:'Difference between Where(), Select(), Any(), First().'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'API Design',title:'Q10 — OTT Backend: Subscription APIs',prompt:'You are building a Netflix-style backend. Users purchase a subscription. Design the APIs.',answer:'At minimum you need Login, Register, Subscription (create/view plan), Payment, Watch History, Profile, Continue Watching, and Logout endpoints. A strong candidate also raises Role-Based Authorization (admin vs regular user) and securing payment callbacks/webhooks — verifying the payment provider\'s signature so a forged request can\'t fake a successful payment.',expected:['Login','Register','Subscription','Payment','Watch History','Profile','Continue Watching','Logout'],followup:'Discuss Role-Based Authorization and secure payment callbacks.'},
    {sec:'Scenario',cat:'Problem Solving',title:'Scenario 1 — 500 Internal Server Error',prompt:'Users are receiving 500 Internal Server Error after deployment. What steps will you take?',answer:'Start with the actual exception details in the logs (Azure Monitor / Application Insights) rather than guessing. Check whether it happens for all requests or only specific ones (points to a data-dependent bug), verify the database is reachable from the new deployment, and if it started immediately after a deploy, consider rolling back while you investigate further.',expected:['Logs','Exception','Database','API','IIS','Azure','Rollback','Monitoring'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Scenario',cat:'SQL Server',title:'Scenario 2 — SQL Server CPU at 100%',prompt:'Your SQL Server CPU suddenly reaches 100%. Application becomes very slow. How will you investigate?',answer:'Check Activity Monitor / DMVs for blocking or long-running queries, look at execution plans for missing indexes causing full table scans, and check for deadlocks. A single badly-indexed query hit repeatedly by many concurrent requests is one of the most common real-world causes of a sudden CPU spike like this.',expected:['Execution Plan','Blocking Queries','Deadlocks','Indexes','SQL Profiler','DMV','Long-running Transactions'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Logic',cat:'Problem Solving',title:'Logical Reasoning — 25 Horses, 5 Lanes',prompt:'You have 25 horses. Only 5 can race at once. Find the fastest 3 using the minimum number of races.',answer:'7 races minimum. Race the 25 horses in 5 groups of 5 (races 1–5), then race the 5 group-winners against each other (race 6) to rank the groups. The overall fastest horse is the winner of race 6. For 2nd and 3rd place, you only need to consider a specific subset — the 2nd and 3rd place finishers from the winning group\'s original heat, the 2nd place finisher from the second-fastest group, and the 2nd/3rd place finishers of race 6 itself — race that subset once more (race 7) to determine the final 2nd and 3rd.',expected:['Logical Thinking','Problem Solving','Approach'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Communication',cat:'Communication',title:'Communication — Explain APIs to a Client',prompt:'Imagine you are speaking to a client with no technical background. Explain "What is an API and why does your application need it?"',answer:'No fixed script — score on delivery. A strong answer uses an everyday analogy (a waiter taking your order to the kitchen and bringing back food, without you needing to know how the kitchen works), avoids acronyms and jargon, and stays confident and concise rather than reciting a technical definition.',expected:['Confidence','Clarity','Simplicity','Client Communication'],followup:null},
