  questions:[
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Next.js',title:'Q1 — React.js vs Next.js',prompt:'Explain the difference between React.js and Next.js.',answer:'React is a UI library — you own routing, data fetching, and rendering strategy yourself. Next.js is a framework built on React that adds file-based routing and lets you choose, per page, how it renders: SSR (fresh HTML generated on every request — good for frequently changing, SEO-sensitive pages), SSG (pre-rendered at build time — fastest, good for content that rarely changes), or plain CSR. SSR and SSG both help SEO because crawlers receive real HTML instead of an empty div waiting on JavaScript. Plain React is fine when you don\'t need SEO or server rendering — e.g. an internal admin dashboard.',expected:['CSR','SSR','SSG','SEO','Routing','Performance'],followup:'When would you choose React over Next.js?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'GraphQL',title:'Q2 — GraphQL Fundamentals',prompt:'Explain GraphQL.',answer:'GraphQL exposes a single endpoint where the client specifies exactly which fields it needs in a Query (read) or Mutation (write), and a Resolver function on the server fetches each requested field. This avoids REST\'s common problems of over-fetching (getting fields you don\'t need) and under-fetching (needing several round trips to assemble what a screen actually needs). REST typically has many endpoints each returning a fixed shape; GraphQL has one endpoint with a shape the client decides on a per-request basis.',expected:['Single Endpoint','Query','Mutation','Resolver','Over Fetching','Under Fetching'],followup:'Difference between REST API and GraphQL?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Prisma ORM',title:'Q3 — How Prisma Works',prompt:'Your resume mentions Prisma ORM. Explain how Prisma works.',answer:'You define your data models in schema.prisma, run "prisma migrate" to generate and apply real SQL migrations, and "prisma generate" to build a fully-typed client. That client gives type-safe CRUD methods and relation queries (e.g. include: { orders: true }) without writing raw SQL by hand. Compared to Sequelize, Prisma\'s schema-first approach gives stronger TypeScript type inference end-to-end and a noticeably cleaner migration workflow.',expected:['Schema.prisma','Generate Client','Migration','CRUD','Relations'],followup:'Why Prisma instead of Sequelize?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'React.js',title:'Q4 — React Performance: 2000 Movies',prompt:'Netflix Home Screen has 2000 movies. How will you optimize it?',answer:'Never render all 2000 cards at once — use windowing/virtualization (e.g. react-window) so only the visible cards are actually mounted, paginate or infinite-scroll the API instead of fetching everything up front, memoize expensive components with React.memo, and wrap callbacks passed to children in useCallback/useMemo so they don\'t trigger unnecessary re-renders. Lazy-load and compress poster images too.',expected:['Lazy Loading','Memo','useMemo','useCallback','Infinite Scroll','Pagination','Virtualization','Image Optimization'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'API Integration',title:'Q5 — Access & Refresh Token Login Flow',prompt:'Design a Login Flow using Access Token and Refresh Token.',answer:'On login, issue a short-lived access token (sent in the Authorization header on each request) and a longer-lived refresh token stored securely — an httpOnly cookie on web. When the access token expires, the client silently calls a refresh endpoint with the refresh token to get a new access token, without forcing the user to log in again. Logout should invalidate the refresh token server-side so it can\'t be reused.',expected:['Login','JWT','Refresh Token','Secure Storage','Token Refresh','Logout'],followup:'Where should Refresh Token be stored?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'API Integration',title:'Q6 — Project Verification',prompt:'Explain one project you built. Explain Architecture, Database, Authentication, Deployment, Challenges, API Integration.',answer:'No fixed answer — this verifies real hands-on experience. Listen for the candidate explaining their own architecture clearly and specifically (actual tech choices and why), rather than a generic description that could apply to any project.',expected:['Architecture','Database','Authentication','Deployment','Challenges','API Integration'],followup:null,redflag:'Cannot explain architecture.'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Coding',title:'Q7 — Coding: Movie List Fetch Component',prompt:'Write a React component that fetches a Movie List using fetch(). Display Loading, Error, and Success states.',code:'const [state, setState] = useState({ status: \'loading\', data: null, error: null });\n\nuseEffect(() => {\n  fetch(\'/api/movies\')\n    .then(r => r.json())\n    .then(data => setState({ status: \'success\', data }))\n    .catch(error => setState({ status: \'error\', error }));\n}, []);',answer:'Track a status field (loading/success/error) alongside the data itself, fetch inside useEffect with an empty dependency array so it only runs once on mount, and conditionally render a spinner, error message, or the movie list based on that status.',expected:['Hooks','useEffect','State','API Handling','Clean Code'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Coding',title:'Q8 — Coding: Sort Movies by Rating',prompt:'Given a movies array with name/rating, return movies sorted by rating.',code:'const movies = [\n  {name:"KGF", rating:9},\n  {name:"Pushpa", rating:7},\n  {name:"Leo", rating:8}\n];\n\nconst sorted = [...movies].sort((a,b) => b.rating - a.rating);',answer:'Spread the array into a new one first ([...movies]) before calling .sort() — Array.sort() mutates in place, so spreading avoids silently changing the original array. The comparator (b.rating - a.rating) sorts descending.',expected:['Array.sort()','Comparator Function'],followup:'Bonus: don\'t mutate the original array.'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'OTT Knowledge',title:'Q9 — OTT Frontend Architecture',prompt:'Design a Netflix Home Page. Explain the components.',answer:'A typical breakdown: Header (logo, nav, profile), Banner (featured/hero content), Categories (genre sections), Movie Row and Movie Card (reusable, used inside every category), Search, Continue Watching, My List, and Footer. A strong answer also discusses folder structure — grouping by feature rather than by file type, and keeping Movie Card fully reusable across every row.',expected:['Header','Banner','Categories','Movie Cards','Search','Continue Watching','My List','Footer'],followup:'Bonus: describe the folder structure.'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'OTT Knowledge',title:'Q10 — System Design: 8s Homepage Load',prompt:'Users complain the homepage takes 8 seconds to load. How will you improve performance?',answer:'Serve static assets and images through a CDN, lazy-load below-the-fold content, paginate the API instead of returning everything at once, code-split the JS bundle so users aren\'t downloading code for pages they haven\'t visited, compress images (WebP), cache API responses, and use SSR so the browser isn\'t blocked waiting on client-side JS just to fetch and render the first paint.',expected:['CDN','Lazy Loading','API Pagination','Code Splitting','Image Compression','Caching','SSR','Bundle Optimization'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Scenario',cat:'Problem Solving',title:'Scenario 1 — Blank White Screen',prompt:'After deployment, users see a Blank White Screen. How will you debug?',answer:'Open the browser console first — a JS error there usually points straight at the problem, often an environment variable present locally but missing in the production build. Check the Network tab for failed asset or API requests, and confirm the environment variables were actually set for that production build (a very common cause of this exact symptom).',expected:['Browser Console','Network Tab','Build Errors','Environment Variables','API','Logs'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Scenario',cat:'Problem Solving',title:'Scenario 2 — 401 Unauthorized on Every Request',prompt:'Your API suddenly returns 401 Unauthorized for every request. How will you investigate?',answer:'Most likely the token isn\'t being attached to requests at all (check the Authorization header is actually sent), the token has expired and isn\'t being refreshed, or the backend middleware\'s validation logic changed. Test manually with Postman using a known-good token to isolate whether the problem is client-side or server-side.',expected:['JWT','Token Expired','Authorization Header','Backend Middleware','Refresh Token'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Logic',cat:'Problem Solving',title:'Logical Reasoning — 100 Floors, 2 Eggs',prompt:'There are 100 floors and 2 eggs. Find the highest safe floor using the minimum number of attempts.',answer:'The optimal strategy needs 14 attempts. Start by dropping from floor 14, and reduce the gap by 1 each time the egg survives (14, 27, 39, 50, 60, 69, 77, 84, 90, 95, 99, 100...) — this balances the risk between the two eggs so the worst-case number of drops is minimized.',expected:['Logical Thinking','Optimization','Explanation'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Communication',cat:'Communication',title:'Communication — Pitch Next.js to a Client',prompt:'Pretend I am a client. Explain "Why should we use Next.js instead of React for an OTT platform?"',answer:'No fixed script — score on delivery. A strong answer frames it in business terms: faster initial load means fewer users bouncing, and server-side rendering helps the platform get discovered in search — rather than diving into technical implementation details the client doesn\'t need.',expected:['Communication','Confidence','Business Understanding','Technical Clarity'],followup:null},
