  questions:[
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'NestJS',title:'Q1 — NestJS Architecture',prompt:'Explain the complete architecture of NestJS.',answer:'NestJS structures an app into Modules (feature boundaries), Controllers (handle incoming routes), Providers/Services (business logic, injected via DI), Middleware (runs before the route handler), Guards (authorization — can this request proceed at all?), Interceptors (wrap the request/response, e.g. logging or transforming the output), and Pipes (validate/transform input data before it reaches the handler). Compared to raw Express, NestJS gives you this structure and dependency injection out of the box, which scales much better across larger teams and enterprise codebases than an unopinionated Express app.',expected:['Modules','Controllers','Providers','Services','Dependency Injection','Middleware','Guards','Interceptors','Pipes'],followup:'Why choose NestJS over Express.js for enterprise applications?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Next.js',title:'Q2 — React.js vs Next.js',prompt:'Explain the difference between React.js and Next.js.',answer:'React is a UI library with no built-in routing or rendering strategy. Next.js adds file-based routing and a choice, per page, of SSR (fresh HTML per request), SSG (pre-rendered at build time), or CSR — plus API routes and image/asset optimization. For an OTT homepage specifically, a hybrid usually wins: SSG or SSR for the page shell and public content (fast first paint, good SEO), with client-side fetching for personalized rows like "Continue Watching" that can\'t be pre-rendered per user.',expected:['SSR','CSR','SSG','SEO','API Routes','Performance','Hydration'],followup:'Which rendering strategy would you use for an OTT homepage and why?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'System Design',title:'Q3 — OTT Backend for 10M Users',prompt:'How would you design the backend architecture for an OTT platform with 10 million users?',answer:'At that scale, split into independently-scalable microservices behind an API Gateway: Authentication, Video/Catalog, Payment, and Notification services. Use Redis to cache hot data (catalog, sessions) and take load off the primary database, a message queue (Kafka/RabbitMQ) for async work like sending notifications or processing payment events, a load balancer to distribute traffic across service instances, and a CDN so video and static assets don\'t hit your origin servers directly. A strong answer also mentions centralized logging/monitoring and horizontal auto-scaling per service based on its own load.',expected:['API Gateway','Microservices','Authentication Service','Video Service','Payment Service','Notification Service','Redis','Load Balancer','CDN','Message Queue'],followup:'Discuss monitoring, logging, and horizontal scaling.'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'PostgreSQL',title:'Q4 — PostgreSQL Performance at Scale',prompt:'Movie table contains 50 million records. Search takes 9 seconds. How will you optimize it?',answer:'Add indexes on the columns actually used in filters/sorts, confirm with EXPLAIN ANALYZE that the query plan is using them rather than scanning the whole table, paginate instead of returning everything, use PostgreSQL\'s built-in full-text search instead of a LIKE \'%...%\' pattern for text queries, partition very large tables by a natural key (e.g. release year), and use connection pooling (PgBouncer) so requests aren\'t opening a fresh DB connection each time. MongoDB trades strict schema and joins for flexibility and easier horizontal scaling; PostgreSQL gives strong ACID transactions and relational integrity — the right choice depends on whether the data is genuinely relational.',expected:['Indexing','Query Plan','Pagination','Full Text Search','Partitioning','Connection Pooling'],followup:'Difference between PostgreSQL and MongoDB.'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Node.js',title:'Q5 — Access/Refresh Token Rotation',prompt:'Explain Access Token, Refresh Token, Rotation, Logout, and Blacklist.',answer:'Refresh token rotation means every time a refresh token is used, it\'s invalidated and a new one is issued in its place — if an already-used (invalidated) refresh token shows up again, that\'s a strong signal of theft, and the whole session/token family can be revoked immediately. Keep access tokens short-lived, store refresh tokens in httpOnly secure cookies, and maintain a blacklist (or track token families) to catch reuse. For multi-device security, track sessions per device so a user can revoke access on one device without being logged out everywhere.',expected:['JWT','Refresh Token Rotation','Expiry','Secure Cookies','Revoking Tokens'],followup:'How would you secure authentication across multiple devices?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Node.js',title:'Q6 — Socket.IO Use Cases',prompt:'Your resume mentions Socket.IO. Explain its use case.',answer:'Socket.IO provides real-time, bidirectional communication over WebSockets (with automatic fallback to polling), plus built-in support for rooms — grouping connected clients — and broadcasting a message to a room or to everyone at once. For an OTT app: real-time chat during a "watch party," pushing a live sports score the instant it changes, or live notifications ("a show you follow just released a new episode") are all natural, practical use cases.',expected:['WebSocket','Rooms','Broadcasting','Chat','Live Notifications','Online Users'],followup:'Can an OTT app use WebSockets? Give practical examples.'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'React.js',title:'Q7 — Project Verification: Colleges18',prompt:'Explain the architecture of Colleges18: Frontend, Backend, Database, Authentication, Deployment, AWS, Biggest Technical Challenge.',answer:'No fixed answer — this checks real ownership of the project. Listen for specific, confident detail rather than generic textbook description, especially around the "biggest challenge" — a strong senior candidate should have a genuine story with a real resolution, not a rehearsed non-answer.',expected:['Frontend','Backend','Database','Authentication','Deployment','AWS','Biggest Technical Challenge'],followup:null,redflag:'Cannot explain own project.'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Coding',title:'Q8 — Coding: GET /movies API',prompt:'Design an API GET /movies with Pagination, Search, Genre Filter, Sorting, Rating Filter.',code:'GET /movies?page=1&pageSize=20&search=leo&genre=action&sort=rating_desc&minRating=7',answer:'Validate every query param server-side (reject bad values with 400, don\'t just silently ignore them), keep the response shape consistent — { data: [...], meta: { page, total } } — and combine filters at the database query level (not by fetching everything and filtering in memory) so it stays fast as the catalog grows.',expected:['Clean API Design','Validation','Error Handling','Response Structure','Status Codes'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Coding',title:'Q9 — Coding: groupMoviesByGenre',prompt:'Write groupMoviesByGenre(movies) that groups an array of movies by genre.',code:'function groupMoviesByGenre(movies){\n  return movies.reduce((acc, m) => {\n    (acc[m.genre] ??= []).push(m);\n    return acc;\n  }, {});\n}\n// [{name:"KGF",genre:"Action"},{name:"Leo",genre:"Action"},{name:"96",genre:"Romance"}]\n// → { Action: [...], Romance: [...] }',answer:'reduce() builds the grouped object in a single O(n) pass — for each movie, it either creates a new array for that genre or pushes onto the existing one. This avoids the O(n²) cost of filtering the array once per unique genre.',expected:['Logic','Object Manipulation','Code Quality','Time Complexity'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'AWS',title:'Q10 — AWS: 20x Traffic Spike Crash',prompt:'Your Node.js server suddenly crashes because traffic increased 20x after a new movie release. What would you do?',answer:'Auto Scaling adds instances behind a Load Balancer as CloudWatch alarms detect rising CPU/traffic, Redis caching takes repeated read load off the database entirely, and a CDN absorbs static/media traffic before it ever reaches your servers. For known traffic spikes (a scheduled release), this should be provisioned proactively — pre-warmed caches and scaling policies — rather than reacted to after the crash.',expected:['Auto Scaling','Load Balancer','CloudWatch','Horizontal Scaling','Redis Cache','Database Optimization','CDN'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Scenario',cat:'System Design',title:'Scenario 1 — Buffering on Mobile Data',prompt:'The OTT app streams perfectly on Wi-Fi but buffers continuously on mobile data. How would you investigate and resolve this?',answer:'This points to Adaptive Bitrate Streaming (HLS/DASH) not adjusting well to lower bandwidth — the player should automatically request lower-quality segments as available bandwidth drops. Check CDN edge coverage for mobile carrier networks, measure actual segment/API latency on mobile vs Wi-Fi, and make sure the client has sensible retry/backoff logic and client-side buffer sizing.',expected:['CDN','Adaptive Bitrate Streaming (HLS/DASH)','Network Logs','Compression','API Latency','Retry Strategy','Client-side Buffer Management'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Scenario',cat:'System Design',title:'Scenario 2 — Duplicate Payment Deductions',prompt:'After deployment, users report some payments are deducted twice. How would you debug and prevent this?',answer:'This is a classic idempotency problem — the same payment request was likely processed twice due to a retry (network timeout, double-click) without protection against duplicates. Use an idempotency key per payment attempt so a repeated request with the same key is recognized and not re-charged, wrap the charge-and-record-in-database steps in a single transaction, and make sure payment webhook events aren\'t processed more than once (webhooks can legitimately fire more than once).',expected:['Idempotency Keys','Transaction Management','Payment Gateway Logs','Retry Logic','Database Consistency','Webhook Verification'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Logic',cat:'System Design',title:'Logical Reasoning — 12 Coins, 3 Weighings',prompt:'You have 12 identical-looking coins. One is heavier or lighter than the rest. Find the odd coin in 3 weighings using a balance scale.',answer:'Split the 12 coins into three groups of 4. Weigh group A vs group B. If they balance, the odd coin is in group C — use the second weighing to compare 3 known-good coins against 3 from group C to narrow it down. If A and B don\'t balance, the odd coin is in the heavier or lighter group; the second and third weighings are used to isolate exactly which coin it is and whether it\'s heavy or light, based on which direction each weighing tips.',expected:['Logical Thinking','Systematic Approach','Explanation'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Communication',cat:'Communication',title:'Communication — Pitch to a CTO',prompt:'Imagine you\'re presenting the Colleges18 project to a CTO. Cover Business Problem, Architecture, Technologies Used, Challenges, and why your solution was scalable.',answer:'No fixed script — score on delivery. A senior candidate should speak with technical depth appropriate for a CTO audience (specific architectural tradeoffs, not just a feature list), while still being clear and structured rather than rambling.',expected:['Confidence','Technical Depth','Clarity','Leadership'],followup:null},
