  categories:['C#','ASP.NET Core','Entity Framework','Redis','SignalR','Background Services','Coding','System Design','Communication'],
  questions:[
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'ASP.NET Core',title:'Q1 — Clean Architecture',prompt:'Your resume mentions Clean Architecture. Explain it with a real project example.',answer:'Clean Architecture separates code into concentric layers: Domain (core business entities, depends on nothing else), Application (use cases/business logic, depends only on Domain), Infrastructure (database, external services — implements interfaces defined in Application), and API (controllers, the outermost layer). The dependency rule is that inner layers never depend on outer layers — Infrastructure depends on Application\'s interfaces via the Repository pattern, not the other way around. This keeps core business logic testable and lets you swap infrastructure (e.g. change databases) without touching business rules — a traditional layered architecture usually doesn\'t enforce that direction of dependency as strictly.',expected:['Domain Layer','Application Layer','Infrastructure Layer','API Layer','Dependency Rule','Repository Pattern','Separation of Concerns'],followup:'Why is Clean Architecture better than a traditional layered architecture?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'SignalR',title:'Q2 — SignalR',prompt:'Explain SignalR.',answer:'SignalR keeps a persistent connection open between client and server (over WebSockets, with fallback to other transports) through a Hub, letting the server push data to clients without them polling. Clients can be grouped, and the server can broadcast to a specific group or to everyone. For an OTT app: live chat during a watch party, real-time viewer counts, live polls during a stream, or pushing a live sports score the instant it updates are all realistic uses.',expected:['Persistent Connection','Hub','Client','Server Push','Groups','Broadcasting'],followup:'Can SignalR be used in an OTT application? Give real examples.'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Redis',title:'Q3 — Redis',prompt:'Explain Redis.',answer:'Redis is an in-memory key-value store, commonly used as a cache in front of a slower primary database, for storing session data, or for pub/sub messaging between services. Keys can have an expiration (TTL), which is ideal for caching data that should go stale after a set time. Avoid Redis for data that needs full ACID guarantees or complex relational queries — it\'s a cache/fast-access layer, not a replacement for your primary database.',expected:['In-memory Database','Cache','Session Storage','Pub/Sub','Expiration','Performance Improvement'],followup:'When should Redis NOT be used?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Entity Framework',title:'Q4 — EF Loading Strategies',prompt:'Difference between Tracking, No Tracking, Lazy Loading, Eager Loading, Explicit Loading.',answer:'The Change Tracker watches loaded entities so EF Core knows what changed on SaveChanges(). Eager loading (.Include()) loads related data up front in the same query; Lazy loading fetches related data automatically the first time it\'s accessed — convenient, but can cause the N+1 query problem if you\'re not careful; Explicit loading lets you manually trigger loading a related entity only when you choose to. AsNoTracking() skips change tracking entirely for read-only queries, improving performance.',expected:['Change Tracker','Include()','AsNoTracking()','Performance'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Background Services',title:'Q5 — Hosted vs Background vs Worker Service',prompt:'Explain Hosted Service, BackgroundService, and Worker Service.',answer:'A Hosted Service / BackgroundService runs long-lived background work inside the app\'s own process, using a CancellationToken to shut down gracefully — good for polling or scheduled tasks. For something like daily report generation, Hangfire is usually the better choice over a raw BackgroundService, because it gives you persistence (jobs survive restarts), automatic retries, and a dashboard for free, instead of building all of that yourself.',expected:['Long Running Tasks','Scheduling','Polling','Async','Cancellation Token'],followup:'Would you use BackgroundService or Hangfire for daily report generation? Why?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'ASP.NET Core',title:'Q6 — Project Verification: Enterprise Licensing Tool',prompt:'Explain Architecture, Authentication, Database, API, Deployment, Challenges.',answer:'No fixed answer — this verifies real ownership of the project. Listen for specific, confident detail about actual decisions made on this project, not generic description.',expected:['Architecture','Authentication','Database','API','Deployment','Challenges'],followup:null,redflag:'Cannot explain project architecture.'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Coding',title:'Q7 — Coding: Movie Subscription API',prompt:'Design POST /subscribe with Subscription Plan, Payment Status, Expiry Date, User Validation.',code:'POST /subscribe\n{ "planId": "premium", "paymentToken": "..." }',answer:'Validate the plan and confirm payment server-side against the payment provider — never trust a "paymentStatus" field the client sends directly, since that could be forged. Compute the expiry date on the server based on the plan\'s duration, and return a clean response model rather than the raw database entity.',expected:['Controller','DTO','Validation','Repository','Response Model'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'C#',title:'Q8 — Coding: LINQ Top 5 Movies',prompt:'Write a LINQ query returning the Top 5 movies with Rating > 8, sorted descending.',code:'var top5 = movies\n  .Where(m => m.Rating != null && m.Rating > 8)\n  .OrderByDescending(m => m.Rating)\n  .Take(5)\n  .ToList();',answer:'.Where() filters to movies with a rating above 8 (and handles nulls explicitly rather than letting a null comparison silently misbehave), .OrderByDescending() sorts by rating, and .Take(5) limits the result to the top 5.',expected:['Where()','OrderByDescending()','Take()'],followup:'Bonus: handle null values.'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'C#',title:'Q9 — Complete JWT Authentication Flow',prompt:'Explain the complete Authentication Flow.',answer:'Login verifies credentials and issues a JWT containing claims (user id, roles) plus a refresh token. Middleware validates the JWT\'s signature and expiry on every request and populates the request\'s claims/identity from it, which Role-Based Authorization checks use to allow or deny access to specific endpoints. Refresh tokens should be stored in httpOnly, secure cookies — never localStorage — to reduce exposure to XSS attacks.',expected:['Login','JWT','Refresh Token','Middleware','Claims','Role Based Authorization'],followup:'Where should Refresh Token be stored?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'System Design',title:'Q10 — OTT Backend for 5M Users',prompt:'Design a backend architecture for 5 million users.',answer:'A Load Balancer distributing traffic across app instances, an API Gateway routing to separate Authentication, Video, and Subscription services, Redis caching hot data to reduce database load, SQL Server for relational data, Docker containers deployed on Azure for consistent scaling, and a CDN serving video/static assets close to users. A strong answer also mentions monitoring, centralized logging, and rate limiting to protect the backend from abuse or accidental overload.',expected:['Load Balancer','API Gateway','Authentication Service','Video Service','Subscription Service','Redis','SQL','Docker','Azure','CDN'],followup:'Bonus: mention monitoring, logging, and rate limiting.'},
    {sec:'Scenario',cat:'Redis',title:'Scenario 1 — Redis Server Goes Down',prompt:'Redis Server suddenly goes down. What happens? How will you recover?',answer:'The app should fail gracefully — falling back to querying the database directly rather than crashing — and rebuild the cache once Redis recovers. This requires designing cache access with a fallback path from day one, monitoring/alerting so the team knows Redis is down immediately, and ideally running Redis in a high-availability configuration (with a replica) to reduce how often this happens at all.',expected:['Fallback to Database','Cache Rebuild','Retry Policy','Monitoring','High Availability','Logging'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Scenario',cat:'System Design',title:'Scenario 2 — Slow App, Normal CPU/DB',prompt:'Your application becomes very slow after deployment. CPU usage is normal. Database usage is normal. Where will you investigate?',answer:'If CPU and DB both look healthy, look outside them: a background service doing blocking work on a thread, slow external API calls the app is waiting on, network latency, or a memory leak causing GC pressure without a dramatic CPU spike. Add detailed timing/logging around external calls and background jobs specifically, since that\'s where time is most likely hiding.',expected:['Memory Leak','Background Services','API Calls','External Services','Thread Blocking','Network Latency','Logging'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Logic',cat:'System Design',title:'Logical Reasoning — 100 Lockers Toggle',prompt:'100 lockers, all closed. Person 1 toggles every locker, Person 2 every 2nd, Person 3 every 3rd... Person 100 toggles only locker 100. Which lockers remain open?',answer:'The lockers that remain open are the perfect squares — 1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36, 49, 64, 81, 100. A locker gets toggled once for every factor it has; most numbers have factors in pairs (6 has 1&6, 2&3), so they\'re toggled an even number of times and end up closed. Perfect squares have one factor that pairs with itself (9 = 3×3), giving them an odd number of toggles — so they end up open.',expected:['Perfect Square Numbers','Explain why lockers with an odd number of factors remain open'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Communication',cat:'Communication',title:'Communication — Pitch to Project Manager',prompt:'Imagine I am your Project Manager. Explain your Carrier Management System project in 3 minutes: Business Problem, Technologies Used, Your Responsibilities, Biggest Challenge, Final Outcome.',answer:'No fixed script — score on delivery. A strong answer stays structured across all five points within the time limit, and speaks about the "Final Outcome" in terms of real business impact, not just a list of technologies used.',expected:['Communication','Technical Depth','Leadership','Confidence'],followup:null},
  ]
