  questions:[
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'JavaScript',title:'Q1 — == vs ===',prompt:'Explain the difference between == and === in JavaScript.',code:'console.log([] == false)  // true\nconsole.log([] === false) // false',answer:'== compares values after converting both sides to the same type (type coercion) — [] == false is true because [] coerces to "" then to 0, and false also coerces to 0. === compares both value and type with no coercion — [] === false is false, since an array is never the same type as a boolean. Best practice is to always use === to avoid these surprising coercion bugs.',expected:['Type Coercion','Strict Equality','Examples'],followup:'What is the output of the snippet above?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'React.js',title:'Q2 — React Hooks',prompt:'Explain React Hooks — difference between useState(), useEffect(), useMemo(), useCallback().',answer:'useState holds a piece of local state plus a setter to update it and trigger a re-render. useEffect runs side effects (data fetching, subscriptions) after render, re-running whenever the values in its dependency array change. useMemo caches the result of an expensive calculation so it isn\'t recomputed on every render, and useCallback caches a function reference so it doesn\'t cause child components to needlessly re-render. In development-only Strict Mode, React intentionally mounts, cleans up, and remounts components once to help surface effects that don\'t clean up properly — that\'s why useEffect can appear to run twice.',expected:['State Management','Side Effects','Performance Optimization','Dependency Array'],followup:'Why does useEffect sometimes execute twice?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Node.js',title:'Q3 — Node.js Middleware',prompt:'Explain Middleware.',answer:'Express middleware are functions that sit between the incoming request and the final route handler, each receiving (req, res, next) and either modifying the request/response or calling next() to pass control along the chain. Application middleware (app.use(...)) runs for every request; Route middleware is scoped to specific routes; Error middleware is a special function with 4 parameters — (err, req, res, next) — that catches errors thrown anywhere earlier in the chain.',expected:['Request','Response','next()','Authentication','Logging','Error Middleware'],followup:'Difference between Application Middleware, Route Middleware, Error Middleware.'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'MySQL',title:'Q4 — MySQL Performance',prompt:'Employee table has 10 lakh records. Search API is slow. How will you optimize?',answer:'Add an index on the columns used in WHERE/ORDER BY, use LIMIT to paginate rather than returning everything, avoid SELECT * (fetch only needed columns), and check the query\'s execution plan (EXPLAIN) to confirm the index is actually being used rather than a full table scan.',expected:['Index','LIMIT','Avoid SELECT *','Query Optimization','Execution Plan'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'AI Concepts',title:'Q5 — What Problem Does LangChain Solve?',prompt:'Your resume mentions LangChain. Explain what problem it solves.',answer:'LangChain provides reusable building blocks for LLM apps — prompt templates, "chains" that link multiple LLM calls or tools together, memory to keep conversation context across turns, and retrieval helpers for pulling relevant documents into a prompt (RAG). Compared to calling the OpenAI SDK directly, LangChain abstracts away a lot of this orchestration — useful for multi-step or stateful LLM workflows, but extra complexity you don\'t need for a single, simple prompt call.',expected:['LLM Integration','Prompt Templates','Chains','Memory','Retrieval'],followup:'Difference between LangChain and OpenAI SDK.'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'AI Concepts',title:'Q6 — Project Verification: AI Recruitment Platform',prompt:'Explain Architecture, Frontend, Backend, Database, AI Flow, Resume Parsing.',answer:'No fixed answer — this checks whether the candidate actually built the AI features or just used a library end-to-end without understanding it. A strong answer clearly separates what they personally implemented (e.g. the API route, the prompt design) from what a library handled automatically (e.g. PDF text extraction).',expected:['Architecture','Frontend','Backend','Database','AI Flow','Resume Parsing'],followup:null,redflag:'Cannot explain AI flow.'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Coding',title:'Q7 — Coding: removeDuplicates',prompt:'Write removeDuplicates([1,2,2,3,4,4,5])\nOutput: [1,2,3,4,5]',code:'function removeDuplicates(arr){\n  return [...new Set(arr)];\n}\n// removeDuplicates([1,2,2,3,4,4,5]) → [1,2,3,4,5]',answer:'A Set only stores unique values by definition, so spreading it back into an array removes duplicates in a single O(n) pass while preserving the original order.',expected:['Logic','Set','Loop','Time Complexity'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Coding',title:'Q8 — Coding: POST /register',prompt:'Write an API POST /register requiring Name, Email, Password, Validation.',code:'POST /register\n{ "name": "...", "email": "...", "password": "..." }',answer:'Validate the incoming fields (proper email format, minimum password strength), hash the password with bcrypt before ever storing it, check the email isn\'t already registered, save the new user record, and return a response that does NOT include the password hash.',expected:['Express Route','Validation','Hash Password','Save User','Return Response'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'Node.js',title:'Q9 — Why Puppeteer?',prompt:'Why is Puppeteer used?',answer:'Puppeteer drives a real headless Chrome browser via code — used for taking screenshots, generating PDFs from web pages, scraping data from JS-rendered pages, and automated browser testing. Compared to Selenium, Puppeteer is generally faster and simpler to set up for Chrome-specific automation, since it talks directly to Chrome\'s DevTools Protocol rather than going through a generic WebDriver abstraction layer.',expected:['Browser Automation','Screenshot','PDF Generation','Web Scraping','Testing'],followup:'Why use Puppeteer instead of Selenium?'},
    {sec:'Technical',cat:'React.js',title:'Q10 — OTT Frontend Components',prompt:'You are developing a Netflix Home Screen. Which React components would you create?',answer:'Navbar, Banner (hero/featured content), Movie Row and Movie Card (reused across every genre section), Search, Continue Watching, and Footer. A strong answer discusses making Movie Card fully reusable — accepting a movie object as a prop — rather than writing separate card components for each row.',expected:['Navbar','Banner','Movie Row','Movie Card','Search','Continue Watching','Footer'],followup:'Bonus: discuss component reusability.'},
    {sec:'Scenario',cat:'Problem Solving',title:'Scenario 1 — Blank White Screen',prompt:'Your React application shows a blank white screen after deployment. How will you debug it?',answer:'Open the browser console first — a JS error usually points straight at the problem, most commonly an environment variable that\'s missing in the production build but present locally. Check the Network tab for failed asset or API requests, and confirm routing/build configuration matches between local and production.',expected:['Browser Console','Network Tab','API','Environment Variables','Build Errors','Routing'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Scenario',cat:'Problem Solving',title:'Scenario 2 — Slow AI API (15s)',prompt:'The AI API takes 15 seconds to generate a response. How would you improve the user experience?',answer:'Don\'t leave the user staring at a static spinner for 15 seconds — stream the response token-by-token if the API supports it so something appears immediately, show a clear loading state (ideally with a cancel option), add a sensible timeout with retry, and consider caching identical repeated requests so they don\'t re-run the full AI call.',expected:['Loading Indicator','Streaming Response','Retry','Queue','Timeout Handling','Caching'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Logic',cat:'Logic Building',title:'Logical Reasoning — 17 Sheep',prompt:'A farmer has 17 sheep. All but 9 die. How many sheep are left?',answer:'9 sheep — this is a wording trap, not a math problem. "All but 9 die" literally means 9 remain alive, regardless of the starting number of 17.',expected:['9 Sheep — a wording/observation trap, not a math problem'],followup:null},
    {sec:'Communication',cat:'Communication',title:'Communication — Pitch to HR Manager',prompt:'Imagine I am an HR manager. Explain your AI Recruitment Platform in 2 minutes without using technical terms.',answer:'No fixed script — score on delivery. A strong answer explains the platform in outcome terms ("it helps recruiters shortlist candidates faster by automatically matching resumes to job requirements") without ever saying "LangChain," "RAG," or "embeddings."',expected:['Confidence','Clarity','Communication','Business Understanding'],followup:null},
